Setup: Introduction Module

Stephanie Spielman for the Data Lab

2022-11-15

Setup

Download Data

This data comes from this 10x Genomics Dataset: https://software.10xgenomics.com/single-cell-gene-expression/datasets/6.0.0/10k_PBMCs_TotalSeq_B_3p.

To get the raw data:

NAME=10k_PBMCs_TotalSeq_B_3p_raw_feature_bc_matrix.tar.gz
wget https://cf.10xgenomics.com/samples/cell-exp/6.0.0/10k_PBMCs_TotalSeq_B_3p/$NAME
tar -xf $NAME
# This gets unpacked into `raw_feature_bc_matrix`


# For posterity, first attempt was with MALT, but it had wildly low ADT counts
# Dataset link: https://www.10xgenomics.com/resources/datasets/10-k-cells-from-a-malt-tumor-gene-expression-and-cell-surface-protein-3-standard-3-0-0
#NAME=malt_10k_protein_v3_raw_feature_bc_matrix.tar.gz
#wget https://cf.10xgenomics.com/samples/cell-exp/3.0.0/malt_10k_protein_v3/$NAME

Split antibody tag data

Before proceeding with further filtering, well want to re-arrange the SCE object to handle the RNA and ADT separately. Currently, the ADTs and genes are both part of the primary experiment, so lets move the ADT counts into an altExp slot.

# We can see this in the `Type` column in the rowData() where the creators of this dataset
#  stored experiment information
unique(rowData(pbmc_sce_raw)$Type)
[1] "Gene Expression"  "Antibody Capture"
# Split out the ADT into an altExp
pbmc_sce_split <- splitAltExps(pbmc_sce_raw, 
                               #"Gene Expression" or "Antibody Capture"
                               rowData(pbmc_sce_raw)$Type, 
                               # The Type which should be the main experiment
                               "Gene Expression")


# The names for the experiments were directly derived from `Type`:
mainExpName(pbmc_sce_split)
[1] "Gene Expression"
altExpNames(pbmc_sce_split)
[1] "Antibody Capture"
# But here on the computer, we don't like spaces, so let's rename it to something informative
#  and space-free, like "CITEseq" or "ADT". We'll use "ADT" since typing less > typing more
altExpNames(pbmc_sce_split) <- "ADT"

# And confirm:
altExpNames(pbmc_sce_split)
[1] "ADT"
# We can do this for main if we want too!
#mainExpName(pbmc_sce_split) <- "RNA"

Filter RNA

First, with DropletUtils

# Filter RNA
droplet_df <- DropletUtils::emptyDropsCellRanger(
  counts(pbmc_sce_split), 
  BPPARAM = BiocParallel::MulticoreParam(4)
) 

# Filter down to low FDR cells and check out dimensions
# Values here are mostly NA.
# NOTE: this filtering does propagate to altExp!! :) 
cells_to_retain <- which(droplet_df$FDR <= 0.01)
filtered_sce <- pbmc_sce_split[, cells_to_retain]
dim(pbmc_sce_split)  # before filtering
[1]   36601 2421702
dim(filtered_sce)  # after filtering
[1] 36601  9248

Now, with miQC

Well need some mitochondria stats for miQC:

filtered_sce <- scater::addPerCellQC(
  filtered_sce, 
  subsets = list(mito = mito_genes))


# See that `sum` is RNA only and `total` is both RNA and ADT
head(filtered_sce$sum)
[1]  6238 13382  7198  6024  5023 13076
head(filtered_sce$total)
[1]  7214 14970  9484  7535  5770 16491
all(filtered_sce$total >= filtered_sce$sum) # total is never going to be LOWER than sum
[1] TRUE

First well build the miQC model and visualize it, including how it suggests to filter the cells.

miqc_model <- miQC::mixtureModel(filtered_sce) 

# Show some miQC plots -
miQC::plotModel(filtered_sce, miqc_model)


miQC::plotFiltering(filtered_sce, 
                    miqc_model)

Now, lets filter based on miQC:

# Apply miQC filtering
filtered_sce <- miQC::filterCells(filtered_sce,
                                  model = miqc_model)

Filter ADT

Were not going to talk about this in depth, since its still an active area of study! But, be aware that RNA and ADTs are treated differently. As always we recommend Orchestrating.

We will focus on only removing cells with cleanTagCounts which will flag cells for removal if there is no detectable ambient concentration, based on an ambient scaling factor that the function calculates. Note that cells with unusally high values also get flagged for removal since the they are assumed to be affected by protein aggregates.

# Run QC on the tags
adt_qc_df <- DropletUtils::cleanTagCounts(altExp(filtered_sce))

Normalize RNA and ADT:

# Normalize RNA
qclust <- scran::quickCluster(filtered_sce)
filtered_sce <- scran::computeSumFactors(filtered_sce, clusters = qclust)
norm_sce <- scater::logNormCounts(filtered_sce)

# Normalize ADT using median counts
baseline <- DropletUtils::ambientProfileBimodal(altExp(norm_sce)) 
median_sf <- scater::medianSizeFactors(altExp(norm_sce), reference = baseline)
sum(median_sf == 0) # make sure nothing is 0!
[1] 0
# Normalize with the median size factors
altExp(norm_sce) <- scater::logNormCounts(altExp(norm_sce), 
                                          size.factors = median_sf)

Dimension reduction

HVGs:

num_genes <- 5000 # 2000? 

gene_variance <- scran::modelGeneVar(norm_sce)
hvg_list <- scran::getTopHVGs(gene_variance,
                               n = num_genes)

PCA:

# Do we want to set the number of PCs?
norm_sce <- scater::runPCA(norm_sce,
                           subset_row = hvg_list)

UMAP:

# Perform graph clustering first
nn_k <- 20
nn_clusters <- clusterRows(
  reducedDim(norm_sce, "PCA"), 
  NNGraphParam(k = nn_k, 
               cluster.fun = "louvain",
               BPPARAM = BiocParallel::MulticoreParam(4)
  )
)

# pop back into sce
norm_sce$nn_clusters <- factor(nn_clusters)

# Add in UMAPs and plot with colors
norm_sce <- scater::runUMAP(norm_sce,
                            dimred = "PCA")
scater::plotReducedDim(norm_sce, "UMAP", colour_by = "nn_clusters")

Cell type annotation from ADTs

We can leverage the ADTs as protein markers to identify likely cell types.

# Again, what are the proteins?
rownames(altExp(norm_sce))
 [1] "CD3"   "CD4"   "CD8"   "CD11c" "CD14"  "CD16"  "CD19"  "CD56"  "CD45"  "IgG1"

Lets explore via UMAPs, for example by coloring ADT counts:


# For example CD8
scater::plotReducedDim(norm_sce, "UMAP", colour_by = "CD8", 
                       point_alpha = 0.6, point_size = 0.25)

# CD4, another T cell marker
scater::plotReducedDim(norm_sce, "UMAP", colour_by = "CD4", 
                       point_alpha = 0.6, point_size = 0.25)

# CD3 which lives on both CD4+ and CD8+ cells
# notice the greens coalescing!
scater::plotReducedDim(norm_sce, "UMAP", colour_by = "CD3", 
                       point_alpha = 0.6, point_size = 0.25)

We can get a bit more sophisticated and look at the the most prevalent ADT across cells:


# Which ADT is the most prevalent for each cell? 
max_adt_indices <- apply(
  logcounts(altExp(norm_sce)),
  2,
  which.max
)
max_adt <- rownames(altExp(norm_sce))[max_adt_indices]

unique(max_adt)
[1] "CD4"   "CD14"  "CD19"  "CD3"   "CD11c" "CD16"  "CD56"  "CD8"  
# Add this into the main SCE experiment for UMAPing
norm_sce$max_adt <- max_adt

What are these proteins, and what cell types might they indicate? In the source quotes below, I have added the bold to the cell types.

  • CD3
    • CD3 (cluster of differentiation 3) is a protein complex and T cell co-receptor that is involved in activating both the cytotoxic T cell (CD8+ naive T cells) and T helper cells (CD4+ naive T cells). This high specificity, combined with the presence of CD3 at all stages of T-cell development, makes it a useful immunohistochemical marker for T-cells in tissue sections. source
  • CD4
    • TCR co-receptor that we can probably assume is mostly on CD4+ T-cells
  • CD8
    • TCR co-receptor that we can probably assume is mostly on CD8+ T-cells
  • CD11c
    • CD11c is a type I transmembrane protein that is expressed on monocytes, granulocytes, a subset of B cells, dendritic cells, and macrophages and may be demonstrated on B-cell chronic lymphocytic leukemia, marginal zone lymphomas, and hairy cell leukemia. source
  • CD14
    • CD14 is a glycolipid-anchored membrane glycoprotein expressed on cells of the myelomonocyte lineage including monocytes, macrophages, and some granulocytes. source
  • CD16
    • CD16 is involved in antibody-dependent cell-mediated cytotoxicity and is expressed on large granular lymphocytes (LGLs) of both NK- and T-cell types. source
  • CD19
    • CD19 is an IgSF surface glycoprotein of 95kDa that is expressed from the earliest stages of B cell development until plasma cell terminal differentiation, when its expression is lost. source
  • CD56
    • CD56 expression is also found in, among others, the hematopoietic system. Here, the expression of CD56 is mostly associated with, but not limited to, natural killer cells. CD56 has been detected on other lymphoid cells, including gamma delta cells and activated CD8+ T cells, as well as on dendritic cells. source

Lets color cells by their most prevalent ADT:

scater::plotReducedDim(norm_sce, "UMAP", colour_by = "max_adt", 
                       point_alpha = 0.6, point_size = 0.25)
